abstract: Black voters, disappointed by 2016, are carefully scrutinizing potential Democratic presidential candidates.
snippet: Black voters, disappointed by 2016, are carefully scrutinizing potential Democratic presidential candidates.
lead_paragraph: BALTIMORE — The first “Amen!” rang out after a couple of minutes, as Senator Elizabeth Warren, speaking to an almost all-black audience at Morgan State University’s winter commencement, described how America has “systematically discriminated against black people.”

abstract: Mr. Zinke is the latest Trump administration official to exit his position facing questions of ethical conflict.
snippet: Mr. Zinke is the latest Trump administration official to exit his position facing questions of ethical conflict.
lead_paragraph: Interior Secretary Ryan Zinke, a key figure in President Trump’s sweeping plan to reshape the nation’s environmental framework, resigned under pressure on Saturday as he faces numerous ethics investigations into his business dealings, travel and policy decisions.

abstract: Can the streaming service’s offerings live up to the joy — and the tears — of the cable channel’s? Our reporter investigated.
snippet: Can the streaming service’s offerings live up to the joy — and the tears — of the cable channel’s? Our reporter investigated.
lead_paragraph: There are two reasons I still pay for cable: 1. NY1 (local news, Jamie Stelter and Pat Kiernan). 2. Hallmark Christmas movies.

abstract: Nelson George, Samuel R. Delany, Major Jackson and others tell us about some of their favorite works of literature.
snippet: Nelson George, Samuel R. Delany, Major Jackson and others tell us about some of their favorite works of literature.
lead_paragraph: For our 2018 Holiday issue, out Dec. 2, T assembled 32 black male writers, who, with their peers, are producing literature that is essential to how we understand our country and its place in the world right now. “When I was asked to consider the particularities of the current landscape, I wondered if a focus on male achievement might obscure the equally unprecedented successes of African-American women,” writes Ayana Mathis in her accompanying essay. “And does that question undermine this extraordinary moment for black male writers?” She admits she hasn’t found a sufficient answer to this question, “but I do know that the work of black women writers presents a ferocious challenge to old sexist perceptions; as [the author and scholar Farah] Griffin says, ‘the difference between this moment and others is that, in the past, to be a black writer was to be a man.’” Here, Nelson George, Samuel R. Delany, Major Jackson and more of the men featured in our pages tell us about their favorite works of literature by black female Americans.

headline_main: 15 Books to Read by Black Female American Writers

abstract: These 32 American men, and their peers, are producing literature that is essential to how we understand our country and its place in the world right now.

headline_main: Black Male Writers for Our Time

abstract: Dozens of possible 2020 Democratic candidates are mulling, weighing, considering, wondering. Here is a guide to how they are communicating a desire to run without announcing it outright.
snippet: Dozens of possible 2020 Democratic candidates are mulling, weighing, considering, wondering. Here is a guide to how they are communicating a desire to run without announcing it outright.
lead_paragraph: The would-be 2020 Democratic contenders could not be clearer: They are not running for president.

headline_main: New York Today: Why Politicians Fear Snowstorms Even More Than You Do

abstract: As she prepares to lead the House of Representatives again, the most powerful Democrat in Washington will have to navigate between a rampaging president and her colleagues’ plans for fighting back.
snippet: As she prepares to lead the House of Representatives again, the most powerful Democrat in Washington will have to navigate between a rampaging president and her colleagues’ plans for fighting back.
lead_paragraph: [In a sign of the strength of a new generation, House Democrats chose Hakeem Jeffries for their No. 5 leadership post over Barbara Lee, a hero to the left.]
